{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "McKernan et al. 2012 McKernan et al., 2018;; Bartos et al. 2017; Tagawa et al. 2020 Tagawa et al., 2021;; Li et al. 2021b; Samsing et al. 2022; Vaccaro et al. 2024).",
    "Given the large observed masses in BBHs, it has also been proposed that at least one of the two BHs composing the detected binary may have already undergone a merger (Miller & Hamilton 2002; Gerosa & Berti 2017; Fishbach et al. 2017 Fishbach et al., 2022;; Rodriguez et al. 2019; Antonini et al. 2019; Kimball et al. 2021; Mapelli et al. 2021; Gerosa & Fishbach 2021; Mould et al. 2022; Fragione & Rasio 2023; Rodriguez 2023).",
    "The processes that stars go through during their lifetime are expected to leave signatures in the BH astrophysical distributions.",
    "For example, stellar winds (Vink et al. 2001; Lamers & Levesque 2017), core-collapse supernovae (Fryer et al. 2012; Schneider et al. 2021), envelope removal after common envelope (Hurley et al. 2002), and pulsational pairinstability supernovae (Heger et al. 2003; Woosley et al. 2015) result in non-negligible mass loss for the star.",
    "In addition to this, there is also the possibility that the BH is not of astrophysical origin, as in the case of primordial BHs (Carr 1975)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "McKernan et al. 2012 McKernan et al., 2018;; Bartos et al. 2017; Tagawa et al. 2020 Tagawa et al., 2021;; Li et al. 2021b; Samsing et al. 2022; Vaccaro et al. 2024).",
    "Given the large observed masses in BBHs, it has also been proposed that at least one of the two BHs composing the detected binary may have already undergone a merger (Miller & Hamilton 2002; Gerosa & Berti 2017; Fishbach et al. 2017 Fishbach et al., 2022;; Rodriguez et al. 2019; Antonini et al. 2019; Kimball et al. 2021; Mapelli et al. 2021; Gerosa & Fishbach 2021; Mould et al. 2022; Fragione & Rasio 2023; Rodriguez 2023).",
    "For example, stellar winds (Vink et al. 2001; Lamers & Levesque 2017), core-collapse supernovae (Fryer et al. 2012; Schneider et al. 2021), envelope removal after common envelope (Hurley et al. 2002), and pulsational pairinstability supernovae (Heger et al. 2003; Woosley et al. 2015) result in non-negligible mass loss for the star.",
    "In addition to this, there is also the possibility that the BH is not of astrophysical origin, as in the case of primordial BHs (Carr 1975)."
  ]
